2+/β�’ ippocampus xhibits m. TORC1-Independent mGluR-LTDIn WT hippocampal slices, LTD induced with the group 1 mGluR agonist, DHPG (50 ΒµM, 10 min), requires mTORC1-dependent signaling and protein translation [18],[28]. Similar to recently published reports [26],[27],[29], we found that DHPG induced a lower magnitude of LTD in 21-d-old juvenile TSC2+/β�’ mice compared to WT mice of the same age (Figure 1a). Consistent with the findings of Auerbach et al. [27], the reduced LTD magnitude in TSC2+/β�’ was restored to WT levels with rapamycin. However, we noticed that at 2 mo of age, LTD in mutant mice was nearly indistinguishable in magnitude from WT (Figure 1c). We sought to characterize this unexplored LTD evident in adult 2-mo-old TSC2+/β�’ mutant mice. To assess the role of mTORC1 activity in adult TSC2+/β�’ LTD, we applied rapamycin to TSC2+/β�’ and WT slices. Consistent with the work of Hou and Klann (2004) [18], rapamycin reduced mGluR-LTD in WT slices (Figure 1d). Surprisingly, rapamycin had no effect on mGluR-LTD in adult TSC2+/β�’ slices (Figure 1e). We recently showed that pharmacological activators of AMPK could mimic rapamycin by inhibiting hippocampal mTOR [30]. Thus, we asked whether the AMPK activator metformin could inhibit mGluR-LTD in TSC2+/β�’ slices. Figure 1f shows that, as with rapamycin, metformin also failed to inhibit mGluR-LTD in adult TSC2+/β�’ slices, but was able to inhibit LTD in WT slices (Figure 1g). This inhibition was AMPK-dependent because it could be blocked by the AMPK antagonist, Ara-A (Figure 1g). Since mTORC1 governs postsynaptic protein translation, we tested the possibility that mGluR-LTD in TSC2+/β�’ hippocampus may also be protein synthesis-independent. Treatment with the general translational inhibitor, anisomycin, eliminated LTD (Figure 1h), demonstrating a continued requirement for protein synthesis for LTD expression in adult TSC2+/β�’. Rapamycin works, in part, by reducing the association of mTOR with its obligate partner protein, Regulatory Associated Partner of TOR (RAPTOR), to reduce activation of downstream targets, such as rpS6 [31]. Since rapamycin failed to impact mGluR-LTD in TSC2+/β�’ slices, we tested whether rapamycin was still capable of reducing RAPTOR-mTOR association in TSC2+/β�’ hippocampus. We immunoprecipitated mTORC1 from slices incubated with DHPG for 10 min in the presence and absence of rapamycin. In the presence of DHPG, rapamycin treatment significantly reduced RAPTOR-mTORC1 binding equally well in WT and TSC2+/β�’ slices (Figure 2a and 2b). Additionally, rapamycin significantly reduced p-S6 levels in WT and TSC2+/β�’ slices in the presence of DHPG (Figure 2c and 2d). These data show that in TSC2+/β�’ slices rapamycin is able to disrupt the mTORC1 complex and inhibit downstream signaling to rpS6. Together, these data demonstrate that the adult TSC2+/β�’ hippocampus maintains a requirement for protein translation for the expression of mGluR-LTD yet appears to have altered signaling that circumvents mTORC1 activity.10.1371/journal.pbio.1001627.g001Figure 1TSC2+/β�’ adult hippocampal slices are unaffected by mTORC1 inhibition.(a) Juvenile (21 d) TSC2+/β�’ hippocampal slices display reduced LTD [79.6Β±3.1%, nβ€�=β€�16(5)] [two-way ANOVA; F(1, 26)β€�=β€�5.72, pβ€�=β€�0.024] compared to WT [70.0Β±4.4%, nβ€�=β€�9(4)]. Rapamycin (20 nM) increased LTD magnitude in TSC2+/β�’ slices to WT levels [68.0Β±3.9%, nβ€�=β€�14(5)]. (b) Rapamycin does not impact juvenile WT LTD [nβ€�=β€�9(3)]. (cβ€“g) Slices from mature TSC2+/β�’ (8β€“12 wk). (c) Mature TSC2+/β�’ [nβ€�=β€�12(4)] show no difference in LTD magnitude from littermate WT [nβ€�=β€�16(5)] controls. (d) Rapamycin (20 nM) reduces mGluR-LTD in mature WT littermates [84.4Β±5.4%, nβ€�=β€�8(4)] [two-way ANOVA; F(1, 18)β€�=β€�17.4, pβ€�=β€�0.0006]. (e) Rapamycin (20 nM) does not affect mGluR-LTD in TSC2+/β�’ hippocampus [70.8Β±5.4%, nβ€�=β€�9(5)]. (f) Metformin (5 ΒµM) has no effect on mGluR-LTD in TSC2+/β�’ hippocampus [63